{"tid":2071622,"cid":18,"subCid":0,"title":"德籍猶太人難民, 1933–1939","createTime":"2020-06-20T03:51:58.000Z","updateTime":"2020-07-07T18:08:14.000Z","uid":105798,"like":74,"dislike":0,"uniUserReply":66,"replies":[{"pid":"d271a086afbc039490d5eddfcb57328e61779df6","tid":2071622,"uid":105798,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-06-20T03:51:58.000Z","msg":"German Jewish Refugees, 1933&ndash;1939<br />\n德籍猶太人難民, 1933&ndash;1939<br />\nsource: <a href=\"https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/german-jewish-refugees-1933-1939\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2Fencyclopedia.ushmm.org%2Fcontent%2Fen%2Farticle%2Fgerman-jewish-refugees-1933-1939&d=WBYYCruE%2BO8aOQq6cZO2w7ccVloK1XwbfTGMhSGe0oU%3D&h=bf0ff26f\" data-auto-link target=\"_blank\">https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/german-jewish-refugees-1933-1939</a><br />\n<br />\n去到1941年之前德國扮歡迎猶太人走<br />\n但實際上做好多小動作唔比猶太人同佢地d 錢走<br />\n<blockquote>Several factors determined the ebb and flow of emigration of Jews from Germany. These included the degree of pressure placed on the Jewish community in Germany and the willingness of other countries to admit Jewish immigrants. However, in the face of increasing legal repression and physical violence, many Jews fled Germany. Until October 1941, German policy officially encouraged Jewish emigration. Gradually, however, the Nazis sought to deprive Jews fleeing Germany of their property by levying an increasingly heavy emigration tax and by restricting the amount of money that could be transferred abroad from German banks.<br />\n</blockquote><br />\n<br />\n希特拉上台之後頭兩年有10份之一猶太人決定走<br />\n但有唔少走錯地方<br />\n去咗其他歐洲國家<br />\n最尾都被納綷捉番轉頭<br />\n<blockquote>In January 1933 there were some 523,000 Jews in Germany, representing less than 1 percent of the country's total population. The Jewish population was predominantly urban and approximately one-third of German Jews lived in Berlin. The initial response to the Nazi takeover was a substantial wave of emigration (37,000&ndash;38,000), much of it to neighboring European countries (France, Belgium, the Netherlands, Denmark, Czechoslovakia, and Switzerland). Most of these refugees were later caught by the Nazis after their conquest of western Europe in May 1940. </blockquote><br />\n<br />\n最先走既係政治活躍既猶太人<br />\n特別係德國唔比猶太人做公務員<br />\n同埋用國家力量打壓猶太人店鋪之後<br />\n<blockquote>Jews who were politically active were especially likely to emigrate. Other measures that spurred decisions to emigrate in the early years of Nazi rule were the dismissal of Jews from the civil service and the Nazi-sponsored boycott of Jewish-owned stores.</blockquote><br />\n<br />\n1935年開始少咗人走<br />\n一黎係d 人見政治情況開始穩定<br />\n二來係美國+歐洲+英聯邦開始唔歡迎猶太難民/ 移民<br />\n<blockquote>During the next two years there was a decline in the number of emigrants. This trend may partly have been due to the stabilization of the domestic political situation, but was also caused by the strict enforcement of American immigration restrictions as well as the increasing reluctance of European and British Commonwealth countries to accept additional Jewish refugees.</blockquote><br />\n<br />\n即使1935年立咗歧視猶太人既法例<br />\n都冇特別多咗人走難/ 移民<br />\n<blockquote>Despite the passage of the Nuremberg Race Laws in September 1935 and subsequent related decrees that deprived German Jews of civil rights, Jewish emigration remained more or less constant.</blockquote><br />\n<br />\n1938年德國食咗奧地利<br />\n猶太人出街會被人打 財產被政府拎走<br />\n呢個時候開始多番猶太人想走<br />\n但想搵國家收留已經唔易<br />\n<blockquote>The events of 1938 caused a dramatic increase in Jewish emigration. The German annexation of Austria in March, the increase in personal assaults on Jews during the spring and summer, the nationwide Kristallnacht (&quot;Night of Broken Glass&quot;) pogrom in November, and the subsequent seizure of Jewish-owned property all caused a flood of visa applications. Although finding a destination proved difficult, about 36,000 Jews left Germany and Austria in 1938 and 77,000 in 1939.</blockquote><br />\n<br />\nSt. Louis 係架客船<br />\n1939年帶住937個猶太人去北美<br />\n古巴 美國 加拿大全部唔比佢地入境<br />\n最尾成船人要番西歐<br />\n估計4份之一人死於集中營<br />\n<blockquote>The sudden flood of emigrants created a major refugee crisis. President Franklin D. Roosevelt convened a conference in Evian, France, in July 1938. Despite the participation of delegates from 32 countries, including the United States, Great Britain, France, Canada, Australia, no permanent or comprehensive solution to the refugee crisis was found. The plight of German-Jewish refugees, persecuted at home and unwanted abroad, is also illustrated by the voyage of the St. Louis.</blockquote>"},{"pid":"fdaa3160d916b6959af282098be852582bfb1dfd","tid":2071622,"uid":105798,"like":32,"dislike":0,"score":32,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-06-20T03:55:00.000Z","msg":"1939年直程多人走去美國度爆quota<br />\n<blockquote>During 1938&ndash;1939, in an program known as the Kindertransport, the United Kingdom admitted 10,000 unaccompanied Jewish children on an emergency basis. 1939 also marked the first time the United States filled its combined German-Austrian quota (which now included annexed Czechoslovakia). However, this limit did not come close to meeting the demand; by the end of June 1939, 309,000 German, Austrian, and Czech Jews had applied for the 27,000 places available under the quota.</blockquote><br />\n<br />\n走埋去日佔上海<br />\n<blockquote>By September 1939, approximately 282,000 Jews had left Germany and 117,000 from annexed Austria. Of these, some 95,000 emigrated to the United States, 60,000 to Palestine, 40,000 to Great Britain, and about 75,000 to Central and South America, with the largest numbers entering Argentina, Brazil, Chile, and Bolivia. More than 18,000 Jews from the German Reich were also able to find refuge in Shanghai, in Japanese-occupied China.<br />\n</blockquote><br />\n<br />\n1941年10月正式落閘<br />\n主要係老人走唔到/ 唔想走<br />\n冇走度既大部份都死於集中營or ghettos<br />\n<blockquote>At the end of 1939, about 202,000 Jews remained in Germany and 57,000 in annexed Austria, many of them elderly. By October 1941, when Jewish emigration was officially forbidden, the number of Jews in Germany had declined to 163,000. The vast majority of those Jews still in Germany were murdered in Nazi camps and ghettos during the Holocaust.</blockquote>"},{"pid":"1003816e6c4904cebf87cb5cadba456982a8d9f5","tid":2071622,"uid":2429,"like":6,"dislike":1,"score":5,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-06-20T03:56:54.000Z","msg":"港豬末日。<img src=\"/assets/faces/pig/cook.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},{"pid":"d32e4b2ae4519b3fe1b67610fcf857d0f3df7cba","tid":2071622,"uid":343134,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-06-20T03:57:37.000Z","msg":"push"},{"pid":"411e5505e162d601dced4740839db089e254b04d","tid":2071622,"uid":105798,"like":54,"dislike":0,"score":54,"citedBy":1,"replyTime":"2020-06-20T04:02:00.000Z","msg":"​tl; dr<br />\n&quot;咦奧利地都係講德文 去奧地利先&quot;<br />\n&quot;人走我先走啦&quot;<br />\n&quot;父母唔肯走&quot;<br />\n&quot;好似安定咗落黎&quot;"},{"pid":"353af5690ffc779e6e71995c93836e6b0578a78b","tid":2071622,"uid":71508,"like":2,"dislike":25,"score":-23,"citedBy":5,"replyTime":"2020-06-20T04:06:42.000Z","msg":"點解唔去以色列"},{"pid":"d0990b6bc617608e3c8f48f740bf74971ecc42ca","tid":2071622,"uid":49044,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-06-20T04:07:37.000Z","msg":"<img src=\"/assets/faces/dog/notcry.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},{"pid":"782379e1a55435b902745c1e1300593d1ce9450a","tid":2071622,"uid":29464,"like":25,"dislike":0,"score":25,"quote":{"pid":"353af5690ffc779e6e71995c93836e6b0578a78b","tid":2071622,"uid":71508,"like":2,"dislike":25,"score":-23,"citedBy":5,"replyTime":"2020-06-20T04:06:42.000Z","msg":"點解唔去以色列"},"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-06-20T04:08:59.000Z","msg":"何不食肉糜"},{"pid":"95e7b28b7d1f8c55807bb6ba83c04ed657f88f8b","tid":2071622,"uid":105798,"like":34,"dislike":0,"score":34,"quote":{"pid":"353af5690ffc779e6e71995c93836e6b0578a78b","tid":2071622,"uid":71508,"like":2,"dislike":25,"score":-